There isn't really a 'flame front' inside a nuclear bomb. The 'energy carriers' inside the reaction are neutrons which travel at nearly the speed of light. The actual explosion is triggered by changing the shape of the fissile material so that more then 1 neutron generated by a a fission event actually stays somewhere inside the material long enough cause more then one decay. Think of it like the "R0" number with diseases, if people don't spend enough time next to eachother on average (without a mask) the disease won't "grow". Making a nuke go critical is just about getting enough of the atoms close enough together to "spread" the decay.

But a decay on one side of the bomb can send neutrons all the way to the other before it causes another decay. So the explosion happens "everywhere" in the bomb at once. (after that x-rays and gamma rays actually cause 'explosion' just from thermal heating of the surrounding material in the bomb and air.)

Terminology suggestion:

Consider not using "turn and burn" for Starship and Falcon 9 maneuvers, but instead using "flip and burn".

"Flip and burn" is used in the series The Expanse to describe a 180deg rotation and then starting up engines in the opposite direction. It is a perfect desciption of the landing maneuver for starship as well as for the boostback burns of Falcon 9 boosters and Superheavy.

"Flip" is more precisely describing a rotation that stops somewhere near 180deg whereas a "turn" can be any angle.

"Turn" also traditionally describes a change in the actual track of the movement as opposed to a rotating around itself while maintaining a course in the same direction.

Additionally it grates on my ears, and I think it must others too, because there is already a completely different meaning associated with "turn and burn". It means that an aircraft in a dogfight is spending its mechanical energy turning very hard and engages the afterburner to replace the energy as much as possible regardless of the high fuel consumption. This will allow it to turn harder, turn hard for longer or build up mechanical energy while turning hard. It is not a momentary thing, it is not a first-this-then-that-thing and it makes it confusing to hear it used about how Starship is going to slam on the brakes when it is usually about keep UP your speed.



Anyway, just a thought that we might stil have time to change this before we get stuck with a bad term for the next 150 years of space travel :D Great work, great chat to read..
